\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Third-party vendor engagements expose the County to risks that no internal control alone can contain:
 supply-chain compromise,
 unauthorized access through contractor systems,
 and data exposure through service providers.
 This policy establishes the operational controls that make vendor engagement defensible —
 clear authority boundaries,
 documented risk assessment,
 binding contractual security terms,
 and auditable offboarding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Operational Boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Business Ownership
\series default
:
 The Department Head of the Requesting Department shall serve as Project Lead.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The Department Head of the Requesting Department shall manage scope,
 timelines,
 acceptance,
 and invoicing.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Technical Enablement
\series default
:
 The Information Operations Department shall provide security validation,
 network connectivity,
 and infrastructure provisioning necessary to support approved engagements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Prohibition
\series default
:
 Information Operations Personnel shall not serve as Project Manager for third-party engagements initiated by other departments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Supply Chain Risk Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Vendor Risk Assessment
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall conduct a risk assessment for each new technology vendor prior to contract execution using the methodology defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Risk Management Policy),
 commensurate with service criticality and data classification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Assessment Approval
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall approve or reject each vendor risk assessment prior to contract execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Federal Covered-Technology Prohibition
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The IT Director shall not procure,
 renew,
 or expand deployment of equipment or services identified as covered under applicable federal restrictions,
 including items appearing on the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) Covered List,
 to preserve eligibility for federal funding and reduce supply chain exposure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The IT Director shall document discovered covered equipment within five (5) business days of discovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The IT Director shall ensure network-level segregation of documented covered equipment within ten (10) business days of documentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The IT Director shall file a replacement plan for documented covered equipment within thirty (30) calendar days of documentation,
 based on risk and lifecycle constraints.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Enhanced Due Diligence
\series default
:
 For vendors with logical access to Confidential or Restricted data (per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
) or to CJI,
 the IT Director shall require at least one independent assurance artifact prior to contract execution,
 such as a Service Organization Control (SOC) 2 Type II report,
 an ISO/IEC 27001 certification,
 an independent security assessment report,
 a qualified third-party penetration-test summary,
 or equivalent independent third-party attestation.
 Vendor-authored questionnaires may supplement but shall not substitute for independent assurance.
 For other vendors,
 the IT Director may require such evidence based on risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3 Contracting and Pre-Engagement Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
No Contract,
 No Access
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall not grant third-party logical access,
 and shall not authorize vendor hardware installation or connection,
 until a contract or formal agreement is fully executed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Data Protection Addendum
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall ensure contracts involving Confidential or Restricted data (per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
) incorporate County-required security and data protection terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
CJIS Security Addendum
\series default
:
 The IT Director (as LASO) shall require incorporation of the CJIS Security Addendum into any vendor contract involving potential logical access to CJI,
 or unescorted access to physically secure locations where CJI is processed,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0 SA-9 (External System Services) and Appendix H.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
CJIS Contractor Certifications
\series default
:
 The IT Director (as LASO) shall ensure that each contractor employee with CJI access is provided a copy of the CJIS Security Addendum and the CJIS Security Policy,
 executes the CJIS Security Addendum Certification,
 and that executed certifications are retained and available for audit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Information Exchange Agreement
\series default
:
 The IT Director (as LASO) shall ensure that any vendor arrangement enabling external access to,
 transmission of,
 or exchange of CJI is supported by a written Information Exchange Agreement (IEA) or equivalent contract language in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
